      NFT Stuff
   =20
 =20

A basic idea in crypto is that things can be simultaneously (1) lucrative a=
nd (2) a joke. Like if someone pitched you on Dogecoin as an investment opp=
ortunity, you would say =E2=80=9Cwell what is good about Dogecoin,=E2=80=9D=
 and they=E2=80=99d say =E2=80=9Cit has a picture of a dog,=E2=80=9D and yo=
u=E2=80=99d say =E2=80=9Cwhat,=E2=80=9D and they=E2=80=99d be like =E2=80=
=9Cha ha ha,=E2=80=9D but also Dogecoin does have a=C2=A0$12 billion market=
 capitalization. For a while its price would go up=C2=A0whenever Elon Musk =
tweeted about it. Was he kidding? Just the wrong question. I   once wrote:
One question that is never worth asking about anything related to cryptocur=
rency is, =E2=80=9Cis this a joke?=E2=80=9D Essentially everything in crypt=
ocurrency is simultaneously serious and a joke. This is partly explained by=
 the history of crypto=E2=80=94crypto is Extremely Online, and everything E=
xtremely Online is both serious and a joke=E2=80=94but it is also something=
 essential to its nature. If I told you that there was a vast oil reservoir=
 in my backyard, that would be either true or not true. Oil is a real physi=
cal substance; you can look at it and touch it and burn it as fuel. But if =
I told you I had a vast stash of Mattcoins, and proposed to give you some f=
or a sandwich or a yacht, we would be on less solid ground. Whether the Mat=
tcoins are a valuable currency exchangeable for sandwiches and yachts, or j=
ust a joke I made up, is a social fact; it depends on what you think about =
Mattcoins, and perhaps on whether you find them funny. Crypto is a form of =
collective storytelling; its truth or falsity does not depend on externally=
 verifiable facts in the world but rather on people=E2=80=99s attitudes tow=
ard it. It=E2=80=99s a parody if you think it=E2=80=99s a parody, but if yo=
u think it=E2=80=99s real then it=E2=80=99s real.
Here I want to be a bit speculative, and I also want to write in all caps: =
NONE OF THIS IS LEGAL ADVICE. But if you have a certain sort of mind, you m=
ight notice a potential legal arbitrage here. The arbitrage is:
=09You intentionally=C2=A0sell people a worthless thing, for real money, wh=
ich you keep.=09If anyone complains =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you get sued or arres=
ted =E2=80=94=C2=A0then=C2=A0you say you were kidding. (But you keep the mo=
ney, which after all is a crucial element of the joke.)=09You kind of were!=
 And kind of weren=E2=80=99t!=C2=A0

Again! I am not recommending this as a strategy! I am just observing certai=
n patterns in the world! But for a while during the initial-coin-offering b=
oom there were a lot of ICOs that explicitly said things like =E2=80=9Cwe a=
re offering a token that is worthless, so we can have money,=E2=80=9D and, =
you know, I hope they had good lawyers.
Or take non-fungible tokens. One common approach with NFTs is that there is=
 some sort of physical or electronic object, and you sell an NFT =E2=80=9Co=
f=E2=80=9D it. The relationship between the NFT and the object is that the =
NFT is a label referring to the object. That=E2=80=99s it. Often you also d=
estroy the physical object: You make or buy a painting, burn it to ashes, a=
nd sell an NFT =E2=80=9Cof=E2=80=9D it; now the NFT is the only =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0version? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0of the artwork. The =E2=80=9Cobject-fire-toke=
n-money   cycle,=E2=80=9D I call it.=C2=A0But this is not essential.   We t=
alked once about a=C2=A0Bohemian prince who wanted money to restore his anc=
estral castle, so he sold NFTs =E2=80=9Cof=E2=80=9D his art collection. If =
you bought an NFT of one of his artworks, (1) you gave him money, (2) he ke=
pt the money and (3) he also kept the artwork. But you got the NFT! Was he =
kidding? Wrong question!
Or early in the=C2=A0NFT craze,=C2=A0people would (try to) sell NFTs =E2=80=
=9Cof=E2=80=9D   the Brooklyn Bridge. They did not own the Brooklyn Bridge,=
 but that=E2=80=99s okay, since they were not selling the Brooklyn Bridge: =
They were selling an NFT of it. Or people would  sell NFTs =E2=80=9Cof=E2=
=80=9D copyrighted digital art that  someone else had created, without acqu=
iring the rights to it or compensating the artist. You might say =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and sometimes NFT platforms did say =E2=80=94=C2=A0well, that=E2=80=
=99s theft, or fraud, or at least copyright violation; surely the artist wh=
o made the underlying work should decide whether to sell NFTs of it, and ge=
t any proceeds.
But the counter-argument is: No, the NFT is a separate thing, not the work =
of art, but a sort of meta-joke about crypto and the financialization of ar=
t. Selling NFTs of someone else=E2=80=99s art is a joke on a continuum with=
 selling NFTs of the Brooklyn Bridge, or selling Dogecoin for that matter. =
You have made a transformative joke: The NFT that you are selling is not=C2=
=A0someone else=E2=80=99s art, it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0your own joke about NFTs (=
and their art). So you own it free and clear, and if you sell it you are no=
t deceiving the buyer or stealing from the artist.
Again! Not endorsing this line of thinking!
  [4]
=C2=A0Just describing the world!  The Wall Street Journal reports:

A self-described entrepreneur and artist in 2021 set out to offer another w=
ay to own a Birkin, with a digital nonfungible token. Mason Rothschild crea=
ted a series of 100 digital images he called MetaBirkins, depicting fur-cov=
ered purses in the same shape and style as the Herm=C3=A8s luxury product, =
which he sold as digital tokens on virtual marketplaces. The NFTs sometimes=
 have sold at prices similar to the real handbags.
Beginning Monday, Mr. Rothschild=E2=80=99s MetaBirkins go on trial in New Y=
ork in a case at the intersection of trademark law and constitutional prote=
ctions for freedom of expression. Herm=C3=A8s is seeking to stop Mr. Rothsc=
hild from using its brand, the destruction of the NFTs and his profits plus=
 other financial damages. Mr. Rothschild says his MetaBirkins are artwork p=
rotected by the First Amendment. =E2=80=A6
In the Birkin matter, Mr. Rothschild received a percentage of each NFT sale=
. He said his project was designed to explore the issue of conspicuous cons=
umption. The images, he said, aren=E2=80=99t replica Birkins, but rather ar=
t that depicts an imaginary bag.
=E2=80=9CMy MetaBirkins project as a whole was an artistic experiment to ex=
plore where the value in the Birkin handbag actually lies=E2=80=94in the ha=
ndcrafted physical object, or in the image it projects?=E2=80=9D Mr. Rothsc=
hild said in a legal declaration.

Sure! You should hack his crypto wallet and steal all the money he got for =
the MetaBirkins, and then say =E2=80=9Cwell that too was an artistic explor=
ation of where the value actually lies, and I found it, and=C2=A0now it lie=
s in my wallet.=E2=80=9D Not legal advice!

