=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  we talked about</a> =E2=80=9Ca TikTok video=
 that said an unnamed company was pulling off a convoluted scheme to manipu=
late housing prices,=E2=80=9D by buying a bunch of $300,000 houses for $300=
,000, then buying one more for $340,000, then selling all 31 for $340,000. =
This is not really all that plausible as a form of market manipulation, but=
 it was empirically true that for a while=C2=A0rising house prices=C2=A0cor=
related to the rise of iBuyers, so you can see where the idea came from.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/30401764.271446/aHR0cHM6Ly9mcmVkLnN0bG91aXNmZWQub3JnL3N=
lcmllcy9DU1VTSFBJU0E/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7a85d0a0" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> home price=
s started falling</a> and iBuyers started losing their shirts. And so you m=
ight expect to see a lot of articles saying, like, =E2=80=9COpendoor is pus=
hing down the price of houses and making them more affordable, all in the p=
ursuit of hilarious corporate losses.=E2=80=9D I mean, I don=E2=80=99t know=
, when I say it like that, I guess you wouldn=E2=80=99t expect to see a=C2=
=A0<em>lot=C2=A0</em>of those articles? But here=E2=80=99s a great=C2=A0one=
! It=E2=80=99s from Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/30401764.271446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMzAvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtaXMtbG9zaW5nLW91dC10by1maXJz=
dC10aW1lLWhvbWVidXllcnMtdGhpcy1ob3VzaW5nLXNsdW1wP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMzAyM19NT05=
FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPT=
IzMDEzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB30ba8435"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">  Prashant Gopal and Patrick Clark</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Individual home-flipper Raad] Yousif punches =
in a code and swings open the door to his most lucrative 2022 flip, a two-b=
edroom town home in this development. He unloaded it last spring, just as t=
he market was starting to sink. Big institutions from Silicon Valley and Wa=
ll Street were still on a buying binge, at times making unbelievable offers=
 sight unseen. In this case a company called Opendoor Technologies Inc. in =
April paid $265,000=E2=80=94$30,000 above the five other bidders, he says.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Opendoor is now asking $218,000, a $47,000 los=
s, not including its fees and renovation expenses. But even that asking pri=
ce is too high, Yousif says. After four price cuts, he smells blood. He=E2=
=80=99s eager to buy back the home he once owned. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s alw=
ays about the right number,=E2=80=9D he says.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes if you find a market maker who is bad at m=
arket making, you should sell to them high and buy back low, like Yousif di=
d. A market maker like that won=E2=80=99t last long, and <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30401764.271446/aHR0cHM6Ly90aGVyZWFs=
ZGVhbC5jb20vMjAyMi8xMi8wNy9pYnV5aW5nLW9uLXRoZS1icmluay13aGVyZS1kb2VzLXRoZS1=
jb250cm92ZXJzaWFsLWhvbWVidXlpbmctbW9kZWwtZ28tZnJvbS1oZXJlLw/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB4741f503" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> many iBuyers didn=E2=80=99t</a>, though Open=
door is still in the business. But you have to take advantage while you can=
.=C2=A0And there=E2=80=99s this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Laurie Tayrien, a former schoolteacher, and he=
r husband, Rick, love the new market. They just snapped up the deal of a li=
fetime for a Phoenix three-bedroom built in the 1980s. Surrounded by golf c=
ourses, below a mountain vista, it was quite an upgrade from their previous=
 home, in a crime-ridden neighborhood.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In November the Tayriens paid $485,000 for wha=
t they call =E2=80=9Ctheir forever home.=E2=80=9D In June the seller, Opend=
oor, had paid $646,800. That=E2=80=99s a 25% loss in just five months. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The couple are busy on a $50,000 renovation of=
 their kitchen, where plywood counters wait to be topped in quartz. The Tay=
riens have the cash in part because of a bungled bet by a big institution. =
=E2=80=9CThey rode a wave, and it=E2=80=99s crashing on them,=E2=80=9D Laur=
ie says. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a corporation. I don=E2=80=99t feel bad for =
them.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course not! What a feel-good financial stor=
y. =E2=80=9CGiant corporations swooped into the market for homes and gave e=
veryone cheap houses, because they were dumb.=E2=80=9D In general, people t=
end to be suspicious of financial intermediation, because the intermediarie=
s are making money and it feels like that must be at your expense. But here=
 the intermediaries were losing money, and that had to be good for someone.=
</p>
